In the report below, I outline some observations about the UCU ballots on pensions and pay in 2018 and 2019. The figures are generally interactive; mouse over the points to see what University is represented.

I have put the data in a convenient xlsx format (unlike the inconvenient UCU data PDFs); this can be found on GitHub, along with the R source code for this report (https://github.com/richarddmorey/UCUballots). I have also created an interactive applet for exploring the ballot results at https://rdmorey.shinyapps.io/ucuballots/.

At the bottom of this document is a searchable, sortable table for exploring the data across Universities.

By necessity, all correlational analyses eliminate those universities that do not exist in both sets (e.g., there are universities in the pay ballot but not the pension ballot).

All analyses are of the strike ballots; the xlsx file also contains data on the action-short-of-strike ballots, but the results are broadly similar and so are omitted here. Both the data table at the end of this document and the interactive app (https://rdmorey.shinyapps.io/ucuballots/) allow exploration of the action-short-of-strike ballot results.

Comparisons between pension ballots, 2018/2019

Ballots mailed

Membership appears to be up from 2018 by about 15% on average. A notable exception to this among the larger universities is University College London, which saw over 50% more ballots sent out in 2019 compared to 2018.

Turnout

Average turnout across universities for the pension ballot was down by about 6% on average from 2018 to 2019.

There were some people I talked to in 2018 who worried that the push for members would affect future votes, decreasing turnout by recruiting people who were less enthusiastic than those members who voted for the 2018 strikes. Although membership did increase from 2018 to 2019, and turnout did decrease from 2018 to 2019, this pattern does not hold true on the level of universities.

The Kendalls correlation between the increase in membership and the increase in turnout is positive but not terribly strong (\(\tau\)=0.099), and the typical caveats about observational data apply. There at least doesnt seem to be any evidence across universities that a boost in membership is associated with a decrease in turnout.

Yes votes

We can also compare the proportion of yes votes across the two years. In both 2018 and 2019, votes were overwhelmingly in favor of striking. In the 2018 ballot, the average yes vote across universities was 87.2%. In 2019, it was lower but still very high at 77.2%. In neither year did any university fail to meet a 50% yes threshold for industrial action.

Of course, this must be qualified by the turnout numbers, because it is the combination of turnout (50%) and yes vote (50%) that determines whether industrial action can take place.

The table below shows the number of universities that had/have the opportunity to take industrial action in each year. Although the same number of universities are involved, and there has not been much change in turnout, and members overwhemlingly favor action, the result is a 25% decline in the number of universities that can take part in the industrial action from 2018 to 2019.

Year N Unis. Unis. threshold % threshold
2018 68 61 89.7
2019 68 46 67.6

Another way of looking at it is by looking at the proportion of members at universities that cannot take part. In 2018, 6.5% of members were not allowed to take part in the industrial action; in 2019, this number is 20%. Assuming membership is roughly proportional to the size of the instututions, this is a dramatic change in the number of employees that can be take part in strike action.

Why the dramatic change? It is all down to how thresholds work (and in this case, are meant to work). If there are a sizeable number of universities just above the turnout thresholdand there will be when turnout is in the mid-50%sthen a small change in turnout can translate into a effect on the industrial action.

But have things changed that much? Not really. If we look at the overall ballot numbers (figure below), it seems the major change is in membership. The number of yes votes has barely changed, and to the extent that the populations of these instututions has remained the same, this means that the proportion of employees voting to strike has remained constant.

Dividing up the vote into universities and then putting a threshold on that vote artificially inflates the differences between years.

Pay vs pensions, 2019

Because there were two votes in 2019a vote on striking over pensions and a vote on striking over pay and casualizationwe can look at the relationship between these two votes.

Turnout was highly correlated across the two ballots, and in fact almost identical. This makes sense, because both ballots were mailed in the same envelope. A discrepancy between these two votes would mean you either intentionally didnt vote in one or the other, or were quite careless.

The votes to strike for pensions and pay/casualization were also highly correlated across institutions. Given that these mostly represent the same individuals voting, this isnt surprising. What is interesting is that the average yes vote across universities for a pay/casualization strike is about 8% lower than that for pensions.

Of course, these are the results only for those universities that were ballotted for both. Of these universities, the results for the pension ballot and the pay ballot are very similar. Yet only about 37% of universities will be allowed to strike over pay, compared to 68% for pensions. What happened?

The table below shows the ballot results broken down by ballot type, as well as whether the university was also ballotted for pension. Those universities ballotted for both tended to meet the threshold at the same rate (about 68%). But the universities not ballotted for pensions tended not to meet the threshold (only 13% did).

Type N Unis. Unis. threshold % threshold
Not ballotted for pensions
pay 85 11 12.9
Ballotted for pensions
pay 66 45 68.2
pension 68 46 67.6

This can clearly be seen in the turnout results for both groups in the figure below.

However, both groups are broadly similar in yes votes, as the figure below shows. The difference between the two groups appears to be turnout, which may indicate an enthusiasm gap, or something else; I dont know.
